<!-- rpn-team.archml — a LIVE multi-agent software build (agent-loop.md §16, milestone 7).
     A lead agent decomposes a real coding goal, delegates the two independent modules to
     two background sub-agents that run in parallel, then integrates their work and verifies
     it by running the tests. All three agents share ONE workspace (root=), so a file one
     worker writes is directly importable by the code the lead writes.

     The lead is NOT given the workers as direct tools — the only signal it has that it can
     delegate is the spawn_agent tool, whose schema enumerates the workers by name ("math",
     "parse"). That is by design (milestone 7): a sub-agent nested in an <m-agent> is a
     background job, discovered by <m-jobs>, not a blocking hand.

     Run (local model):
       MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE="$(cat the-objective)" \
         bun meditator.js -a architecture/agents/rpn-team.archml -mp local-dev -->
<m-agent name="architect"
         memory="rpn-team"
         interlocutor="user"
         model="voice"
         utilityModel="utility"
         maxSteps="48"
         stopWhen="no-tools">
  You are the ARCHITECT of a small team of coding agents, working together in one shared
  workspace. You are given a software goal that decomposes into independent pieces. Your job:
  size it up, hand each independent piece to a background worker with spawn_agent (giving it a
  precise, self-contained spec — the exact filename to create and the exact interface it must
  expose), and run the pieces in PARALLEL by handing them to different workers. While they
  work you can prepare the integration. Poll a job with check, or block on one with wait when
  you have nothing else to do; you will also be told when a job finishes. Once every worker's
  file is in the workspace, write the integrating code and the tests YOURSELF, run the tests
  with the terminal, and read the real output. Never claim success until you have actually SEEN
  the tests pass. When everything passes, reply with a short summary and no tool call.

  <m-objective name="objective">
    Build a small RPN (reverse Polish notation) calculator in Python. (The concrete spec is
    supplied at wake.)
  </m-objective>

  <!-- The architect's own reasoner. Declared FIRST so `reason/reply` resolves to it, not to
       a worker's identically-named reasoner (name-based ref: first in document order wins). -->
  <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>

  <!-- The architect's own belt: read the workers' files, write the integration + tests, run
       them. All rooted in the SHARED workspace. -->
  <m-read-file  name="read_file"  root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-read-file>
  <m-write-file name="write_file" root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-write-file>
  <m-edit       name="edit"       root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-edit>
  <m-terminal   name="terminal"   root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace" wall="60s" network="off"></m-terminal>

  <!-- WORKER 1: the arithmetic module. Its own full belt, rooted in the SAME workspace. -->
  <m-agent name="math" role="subagent" maxSteps="22" stopWhen="finish-tool">
    You are a worker agent. You are given a precise spec for ONE Python module. Write exactly
    that file (the given filename) in the shared workspace, then run it with the terminal
    (python3 <file>) to check its self-test passes. Read the real output; if it errors, fix the
    file and run again. Call finish(summary) only once the file exists and its self-test runs
    clean — say plainly what you built.

    <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>
    <m-write-file name="write_file" root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-write-file>
    <m-read-file  name="read_file"  root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-read-file>
    <m-edit       name="edit"       root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-edit>
    <m-terminal   name="terminal"   root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace" wall="60s" network="off"></m-terminal>
    <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>
  </m-agent>

  <!-- WORKER 2: the tokenizer module. Independent of worker 1, same workspace. -->
  <m-agent name="parse" role="subagent" maxSteps="22" stopWhen="finish-tool">
    You are a worker agent. You are given a precise spec for ONE Python module. Write exactly
    that file (the given filename) in the shared workspace, then run it with the terminal
    (python3 <file>) to check its self-test passes. Read the real output; if it errors, fix the
    file and run again. Call finish(summary) only once the file exists and its self-test runs
    clean — say plainly what you built.

    <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>
    <m-write-file name="write_file" root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-write-file>
    <m-read-file  name="read_file"  root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-read-file>
    <m-edit       name="edit"       root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"></m-edit>
    <m-terminal   name="terminal"   root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace" wall="60s" network="off"></m-terminal>
    <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>
  </m-agent>

  <!-- ASYNC AGENCY: discovers "math" and "parse" and offers spawn_agent alongside the shell
       job tools. Sub-agent jobs and shell jobs share one registry, so check/wait/kill/list_jobs
       collect both. Long waits because a worker's whole loop can take a while on a local model. -->
  <m-jobs name="jobs" root="/home/sovereign/Meditator/memory/rpn-team/workspace"
          wall="10m" defaultWait="200s" maxWait="600s" network="off"></m-jobs>

  <!-- The architect's own stall guard. -->
  <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="4" haltAt="10"></m-repeat-guard>
</m-agent>
